{"title_page": "Neal I. Rosenthal", "text_new": "{{short description|American author & wine merchant}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{infobox person\n|name = Neal I. Rosenthal\n|image = Neal Rosenthal.jpg\n|alt =\n|caption =\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1945|10|14}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n|alma_mater = [[Rutgers University]], [[New York University]], [[Columbia University]]\n|occupation = [[Author]]<br />[[Wine merchant]]\n|years_active = 1977-present\n|spouse = {{married|Kerry Madigan|2002}} <ref name=nytimes1>{{cite news |last1=Wadler |first1=Joyce |title=In Dutchess County, a Wine Merchant\u2019s Renovated Home |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/19/garden/19rosenthal.html |work=The New York Times |date=19 June 2008}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Neal I. Rosenthal''' (born 1945) is an American [[author]], [[entrepreneur]], and wine merchant.\n\n==Early life==\n\nNeal I. Rosenthal was born in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] in 1945 and was educated at [[Rutgers University]] (B.A.), [[Columbia University]] (J.D.),<ref name=nytimes1 /> and [[New York University]] (LL.M.).<ref>{{cite web |title=Astor Center NYC |url=https://www.astorcenternyc.com/instructor-neal-rosenthal.ac}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n[[Neal I. Rosenthal]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Neal I. Rosenthal |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neal_Rosenthal}}</ref> is the founder of Rosenthal Wine Merchant (RWM) and The Mad Rose Group (MRG).<ref name=nytimes2>{{cite news |last1=Fabricant |first1=Florence |title=A Wine Importer Turns to Food |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/26/dining/mad-rose-foods.html |work=The New York Times |date=26 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1\"/> RWM imports and distributes limited production, estate-bottled wines from [[Western Europe]]. This endeavor began in 1977 as a one-man retail operation in [[New York City]], when Neal stepped away from his law practice to conceive a project that would operate outside the mainstream wine business with special emphasis on supporting artisanal, family-owned and operated wine estates.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Huyghe |first1=Cathy |title=Two Wine Insider Secrets, Courtesy Of Neal Rosenthal And His Newest Venture |journal=Forbes |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/cathyhuyghe/2018/04/30/two-wine-insider-secrets-courtesy-of-neal-rosenthal-and-his-newest-venture/#325dd75a35a9 |language=en}}</ref>\nNeal<ref>{{cite web |title=Neal I. Rosenthal |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neal_I._Rosenthal}}</ref> was joined shortly thereafter by Kerry Madigan, who later became his partner and wife. The two have spent decades working with those who share the RWM passion for terroir, collaborating with growers in [[France]], [[Italy]], [[Switzerland]] and [[Catalonia]] who produce limited quantities of the finest quality wines. MRG now includes Mad Rose Specialty Foods<ref>{{cite web |title=NY Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/26/dining/mad-rose-foods.html}}</ref> (importer, distributor and direct-to-consumer purveyor of Italian and French food specialties, including most importantly a range of extra virgin olive oils), Mad Rose Journeys, a selection of intimate trips throughout [[Europe]] personally led and inspired by Neal's deep connections to the sights, tastes, people, and secrets of Western Europe, and La Closerie les Capucines, a 17th-century stone maison d\u2019h\u00f4te in Arbois in the Jura region of northeastern [[France]]. \n\nIn 2006, Neal created The Mad Rose Foundation, a charitable organization that supports among other objectives public school education, literary organizations, free speech initiatives, and programs to protect the environment.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pro Publica |url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/208014253}}</ref> Currently, the Foundation is underwriting a study abroad program in Benin in West Africa in collaboration with Rutgers University.\n<ref name=nytimes2 />\n\n=Achievements=\nNeal is the author of Reflections of a Wine Merchant, published by Farrar, Straus & Giroux in 2008. He is featured in the documentary film [[Mondovino]] that debuted at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite book |title=Reflections of a wine merchant |publisher=Farrar, Straus Giroux |isbn=978-0374531782}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Neal Rosenthal |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1711770/ |website=IMDb}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Neal was nominated for an Outstanding Wine & Spirits Professional Award by the [[James Beard Foundation Award]]. \n<ref>{{cite web |last1=February 21 |first1=Paolo Lucchesi on |last2=AM |first2=Paolo Lucchesi on |title=2012 James Beard Award Semifinalists announced, with lots of Bay Area faces |url=https://insidescoopsf.sfgate.com/blog/2012/02/21/2012-james-beard-award-semifinalists-announced-with-lots-of-bay-area-faces/ |website=Inside Scoop SF |date=21 February 2012}}</ref>\nIn 2019, Neal was awarded honorary citizenship in the village of [[Carema]] in northwestern Piedmont in [[Italy]] in recognition of his efforts to promote the rare wines of that region.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fiera di Primavera a Carema nel segno della zootecnia |url=http://www.piemontetopnews.it/fiera-di-primavera-a-carema-nel-segno-della-zootecnia/ |work=PiemonteTopNews |language=it-IT}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenthal, Neal}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n\n\n{{US-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American author & wine merchant}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{infobox person\n|name = Neal I. Rosenthal\n|image = Neal Rosenthal.jpg\n|alt =\n|caption =\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1945|10|14}}\n|birth_place = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n|alma_mater = [[Rutgers University]], [[New York University]], [[Columbia University]]\n|occupation = [[Author]]<br />[[Wine merchant]]\n|years_active = 1977-present\n|spouse = {{married|Kerry Madigan|2002}} <ref name=nytimes1>{{cite news |last1=Wadler |first1=Joyce |title=In Dutchess County, a Wine Merchant\u2019s Renovated Home |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/19/garden/19rosenthal.html |work=The New York Times |date=19 June 2008}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Neal I. Rosenthal''' (born 1945) is an American [[author]], [[entrepreneur]], and wine merchant.\n\n==Early life==\n\nNeal I. Rosenthal was born in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] in 1945 and was educated at [[Rutgers University]] (B.A.), [[Columbia University]] (J.D.),<ref name=nytimes1 /> and [[New York University]] (LL.M.).<ref>{{cite web |title=Astor Center NYC |url=https://www.astorcenternyc.com/instructor-neal-rosenthal.ac}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n[[Neal I. Rosenthal]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Neal I. Rosenthal |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neal_Rosenthal}}</ref> is the founder of Rosenthal Wine Merchant (RWM) and The Mad Rose Group (MRG).<ref name=nytimes2>{{cite news |last1=Fabricant |first1=Florence |title=A Wine Importer Turns to Food |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/26/dining/mad-rose-foods.html |work=The New York Times |date=26 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1\"/> RWM imports and distributes limited production, estate-bottled wines from [[Western Europe]]. This endeavor began in 1977 as a one-man retail operation in [[New York City]], when Neal stepped away from his law practice to conceive a project that would operate outside the mainstream wine business with special emphasis on supporting artisanal, family-owned and operated wine estates.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Huyghe |first1=Cathy |title=Two Wine Insider Secrets, Courtesy Of Neal Rosenthal And His Newest Venture |journal=Forbes |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/cathyhuyghe/2018/04/30/two-wine-insider-secrets-courtesy-of-neal-rosenthal-and-his-newest-venture/#325dd75a35a9 |language=en}}</ref>\nNeal<ref>{{cite web |title=Neal I. Rosenthal |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neal_I._Rosenthal}}</ref> was joined shortly thereafter by Kerry Madigan, who later became his partner and wife. The two have spent decades working with those who share the RWM passion for terroir, collaborating with growers in [[France]], [[Italy]], [[Switzerland]] and [[Catalonia]] who produce limited quantities of the finest quality wines. MRG now includes Mad Rose Specialty Foods<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/26/dining/mad-rose-foods.html}}</ref> (importer, distributor and direct-to-consumer purveyor of Italian and French food specialties, including most importantly a range of extra virgin olive oils), Mad Rose Journeys, a selection of intimate trips throughout [[Europe]] personally led and inspired by Neal's deep connections to the sights, tastes, people, and secrets of Western Europe, and La Closerie les Capucines, a 17th-century stone maison d\u2019h\u00f4te in Arbois in the Jura region of northeastern [[France]]. \n\nIn 2006, Neal created The Mad Rose Foundation, a charitable organization that supports among other objectives public school education, literary organizations, free speech initiatives, and programs to protect the environment.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/208014253}}</ref> Currently, the Foundation is underwriting a study abroad program in Benin in West Africa in collaboration with Rutgers University.\n<ref name=nytimes2 />\n\n=Achievements=\nNeal is the author of Reflections of a Wine Merchant, published by Farrar, Straus & Giroux in 2008. He is featured in the documentary film [[Mondovino]] that debuted at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite book |title=Reflections of a wine merchant |publisher=Farrar, Straus Giroux |isbn=978-0374531782}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |title=Neal Rosenthal |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1711770/ |website=IMDb}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Neal was nominated for an Outstanding Wine & Spirits Professional Award by the [[James Beard Foundation Award]]. \n<ref>{{cite web |last1=February 21 |first1=Paolo Lucchesi on |last2=AM |first2=Paolo Lucchesi on |title=2012 James Beard Award Semifinalists announced, with lots of Bay Area faces |url=https://insidescoopsf.sfgate.com/blog/2012/02/21/2012-james-beard-award-semifinalists-announced-with-lots-of-bay-area-faces/ |website=Inside Scoop SF |date=21 February 2012}}</ref>\nIn 2019, Neal was awarded honorary citizenship in the village of [[Carema]] in northwestern Piedmont in [[Italy]] in recognition of his efforts to promote the rare wines of that region.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fiera di Primavera a Carema nel segno della zootecnia |url=http://www.piemontetopnews.it/fiera-di-primavera-a-carema-nel-segno-della-zootecnia/ |work=PiemonteTopNews |language=it-IT}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenthal, Neal}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n\n\n{{US-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jhindermahal", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neal_I._Rosenthal"}
